{"title_page": "Helen Edmundson", "text_new": "{{short description|British playwright and screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Helen Edmundson\n| birth_date    = 1964\n| birth_place   = Liverpool, England, UK\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = Playwright, Screenwriter\n}}\n\n'''Helen Edmundson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 1964) is a British [[playwright]] and [[screenwriter]]. She has won awards and critical acclaim both for her original writing and for her adaptations of various literary classics for the stage and screen.\n\n==Early life==\nEdmundson was born in [[Liverpool]], in 1964.<ref name=\"clearing\">{{cite book|last1=Edmundson|first1=Helen|title=The Clearing|date=2002|publisher=Nick Hern Books|location=London|isbn=1854592815}}</ref> Most of her childhood was spent on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]] and in [[Chester]].<ref name=\"clearing\"/> Edmundson studied drama at [[Manchester University]].<ref name=\"clearing\"/> After her studies, Edmundson acted with Red Stockings, a female agit-prop company, for whom she wrote the musical comedy ''Ladies in the Lift'' in 1988.<ref name=\"clearing\"/> This was her first solo attempt at writing for the stage. After leaving Red Stockings, she acted throughout northwest England.<ref name=\"clearing\"/>\n\n==Theatre==\n===1990s===\nEdmundson's first play ''Flying'' was produced at the [[National Theatre Studio]] in 1990. In 1992, her adaptation of ''[[Anna Karenina]]'', produced by [[Shared Experience]], won a [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] Award and a [[Theatre Awards UK|TMA Award]]; the production toured nationally and internationally.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nickhernbooks.co.uk/helen-edmundson|title=Nick Hern Books &#124; About Helen Edmundson|website=Nick Hern Books|accessdate=Oct 9, 2019}}</ref> In 1993, Edmundson's original play ''The Clearing'', which won the [[John Whiting Award]], was staged at the [[Bush Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre--civil-strife-paul-taylor-reviews-helen-edmundsons-the-clearing-at-the-bush-1507694.html|title=THEATRE / Civil strife: Paul Taylor reviews Helen Edmundson's The|publisher=}}</ref> In 1994, her adaptation of ''[[The Mill on the Floss]]'' was also produced by Shared Experience, again touring nationally and internationally; Edmundson won a Time Out Award for ''The Clearing'' and ''The Mill on the Floss''.<ref name=\"windhamcampbell.org\">{{cite web|url=http://windhamcampbell.org/2015/winner/helen-edmundson|title=Helen Edmundson|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> In 1996, Shared Experience staged her adaptation of ''[[War and Peace]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/war-of-the-words-1338952.html|title=War of the words|publisher=}}</ref> in a production starring [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA Award]]-nominee [[Anne-Marie Duff]]; the play was nominated for a Writers' Guild Award for Best Play.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2002, Edmundson's play ''Mother Teresa is Dead'' was produced at the [[Royal Court Theatre]]. In 2004, her adaptation of ''Gone to Earth'' was produced by Shared Experience at the [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)|Lyric Hammersmith]] and on tour; it was nominated for a [[TMA Award]].<ref name=\"londontheatre.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.londontheatre.co.uk/londontheatre/news/sep04/17sep04tma.htm|title=TMA Theatre Awards 2004 nominations announced|date=8 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Edmundson's adaptation of ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]'' premiered at the National Theatre in November 2005, starring [[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]]-winner [[Bertie Carvel]] and [[Tony Award]]-nominee [[Paul Ritter (actor)|Paul Ritter]]; Edmundson received a Time Out Award and was nominated for an Olivier Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/nov/16/theatre|author=[[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]]|title=Coram Boy|date=16 November 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"olivierawards.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/winners/view/item98373/olivier-winners-2006/|title=Olivier Winners 2006|publisher=}}</ref> The play came back for a revival at the same venue a year later, again starring Carvel. Her adaptation of ''[[Orestes (play)|Orestes]]'', toured in the UK and played at the [[Tricycle Theatre]] with Shared Experience in 2006. ''Coram Boy'' was revived at the [[Imperial Theatre]] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 2007, starring [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]-winner [[Uzo Aduba]] and Tony Award-nominee [[Jan Maxwell]], receiving six Tony Award nominations. In 2008, Edmundson amended her adaptation of ''War and Peace'', turning it into a two-part play; this production was staged by Shared Experience and Nottingham Playhouse before touring. In the same year, her musical adaptation of ''[[Zorro (musical)|Zorro]]'' was produced at the [[Garrick Theatre]], starring Olivier Award-winner [[Lesli Margherita]] and Olivier Award-nominee [[Emma Williams (actress)|Emma Williams]]; Edmundson was nominated for an Olivier Award for Best New Musical.<ref name=\"olivierawards.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/winners/view/item106339/olivier-winners-2009/|title=Olivier Awards Winners 2009 -Official London Theatre|publisher=}}</ref> In 2009, Edmundson's adaptation of ''[[Life Is a Dream]]'' was produced at the [[Donmar Warehouse]], starring BAFTA Award-winner [[Dominic West]].\n\n===2010s===\nIn 2010, Edmundson's musical adaptation of ''[[Swallows and Amazons]]'' was first produced at the [[Bristol Old Vic]], directed by Tony Award-winner [[Tom Morris (director)|Tom Morris]]. The next year, the show transferred to the [[Vaudeville Theatre]]; the play was nominated for an [[Evening Standard Theatre Award]].<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/evening-standard-theatre-awards-adrian-lester-and-his-writer-wife-lolita-chakrabarti-shortlisted-8306478.html|title=Evening Standard Theatre Awards: Adrian Lester and his writer wife|publisher=}}</ref> Edmundson took part in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s 2011 project ''[[Sixty-Six Books]]'', for which artists wrote a piece based upon a book of the [[King James Bible]]; Edmundson wrote a piece entitled ''In the night, a promise'', based on ''[[Book of Zephaniah|Zephaniah]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090950/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |archivedate=2011-07-04 }}</ref> The same year, her adaptation of ''Coram Boy'' was revived at the Bristol Old Vic. In 2012, her play about [[Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz]], ''[[The Heresy of Love]]'', was produced by the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Swan Theatre (Stratford)|Swan Theatre]] in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].<ref>[http://www.rsc.org.uk/explore/other-writers/the-heresy-of-love.aspx ''The Heresy of Love''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414053138/http://www.rsc.org.uk/explore/other-writers/the-heresy-of-love.aspx |date=2014-04-14 }}, RSC.</ref> The same year, Edmundson's adaptation of ''Swallows and Amazons'' was revived for a national tour. Also in 2012, Edmundson's play ''Mary Shelley'' was produced on a nationwide tour, including the Tricycle Theatre and the [[Liverpool Playhouse]], by Shared Experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sharedexperience.org.uk/maryshelley.html|title=Shared Experience - Productions - Mary Shelley|first=|last=?|website=www.sharedexperience.org.uk}}</ref> In 2013, her adaptation of ''[[Mephisto (novel)|Mephisto]]'' was produced at the [[Altonaer Theater]] in [[Hamburg]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dramaonlinelibrary.com/playwrights/helen-edmundson-iid-135921|title=Edmundson, Helen - Drama Online|website=www.dramaonlinelibrary.com|accessdate=Oct 9, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Edmundson's adaptation of the novel ''[[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Raquin]]'' was produced at the [[Theatre Royal, Bath]], starring Olivier Award-winners [[Alison Steadman]] and [[Desmond Barrit]]. In 2015, ''The Heresy of Love'' was revived for a run at [[Shakespeare's Globe]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Heresy of Love |url=http://www.shakespearesglobe.com/discovery-space/previous-productions/the-heresy-of-love |website=Shakespeare's Globe |accessdate=20 September 2018 |year=2015}}. Written by Helen Edmundson and directed by John Dove.</ref> Edmundson's adaptation of ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Raquin'' was produced by [[Roundabout Theatre Company]] at [[Studio 54]] on Broadway from 2015 to 2016, starring [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-nominee [[Keira Knightley]] and Tony Award-winner [[Judith Light]]; the play was nominated for Outstanding New Broadway Play at the 2016 [[Outer Critics Circle Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/things-to-do/therese-raquin|title=Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Raquin - Theater in New York|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-ThereseRaquin-Knightly-2015>{{cite news|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse|title=Keira Knightley, Making Her Broadway Debut, Is Not Afraid of the Dark|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/25/theater/keira-knightley-making-her-broadway-debut-is-not-afraid-of-the-dark.html|accessdate=21 October 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=21 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/2016-outer-critics-circle-nominees-announced-com-347165|title=2016 Outer Critics Circle Nominees Announced - Playbill|website=Playbill}}</ref> Simultaneously, the RSC premiered her play ''[[Queen Anne (play)|Queen Anne]]'' in Stratford.<ref>Matthew Hemley, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/production/2015/02/rsc-unveils-winter-2015-season-antony-sher-lear/ \"RSC unveils winter 2015 season and Antony Sher as Lear\"], ''The Stage''.</ref> In 2017, the RSC produced ''Queen Anne'' at the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]], starring [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]]-winner [[Romola Garai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-38831153|title=Romola Garai takes on aristocratic role|date=1 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2017/feb/01/royal-shakespeare-company-to-stage-robert-harriss-cicero-trilogy|title=Royal Shakespeare Company to stage Robert Harris's Cicero trilogy|first=Maev|last=Kennedy|date=1 February 2017|website=the Guardian}}</ref> From April to August 2019, Edmundson's adaptation of ''[[Small Island (novel)|Small Island]]'' was produced at the National Theatre, directed by its artistic director, Olivier Award-nominee [[Rufus Norris]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/oct/03/andrea-levys-small-island-novel-to-be-staged-next-year|title=Andrea Levy's Small Island novel to be staged next year|first=Mark Brown Arts|last=correspondent|date=Oct 3, 2018|accessdate=Oct 9, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the play one of the top two theatre shows of 2019.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/dec/17/top-10-theatre-shows-of-2019</ref>\n\n===2020s===\nEdmundson's adaptation of ''Small Island'' will be revived at the National Theatre in October 2020, again directed by Norris.<ref>https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/national-2020-kristin-scott-thomas-phaedra_50970.html</ref>\n\n==Film and television==\nEdmundson has written two short films for television: ''One Day'', broadcast on [[BBC Two]] in July 1991,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbctwo/england/1991-07-25|title=BBC Two England - 25 July 1991 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and ''Stella'' for [[Channel 4]]. In 2015, she wrote two episodes of [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] drama ''[[The Suspicions of Mr Whicher]]'', ''Beyond the Pale'' and ''The Ties that Bind'', starring [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]]-winners [[Paddy Considine]] and [[Tim Pigott-Smith]]. In September of the same year, Edmundson's feature-length adaptation of ''[[An Inspector Calls (2015 TV film)|An Inspector Calls]]'', starring BAFTA Award-winners [[David Thewlis]] and [[Miranda Richardson]], was broadcast on [[BBC One]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/sep/14/bbc-an-inspector-calls-this-is-england-90|title=BBC's An Inspector Calls arrests nearly 6 million viewers|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=14 September 2015|website=the Guardian}}</ref> the adaptation won the 2016 [[Broadcasting Press Guild]] Award for Best Single Drama<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingpressguild.org/bpgawards/bpg-awards-2016/|title=2016|date=12 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and was nominated for two 2016 [[British Academy Television Craft Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2016/tvcraft|title=Television Craft in 2016 - BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org}}</ref> In 2018, Edmundson wrote the film ''[[Mary Magdalene (2018 film)|Mary Magdalene]]'', which was directed by Emmy Award-nominee [[Garth Davis]] and starred Academy Award-nominees [[Rooney Mara]] and [[Joaquin Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/21/kings-speech-producer-see-saw-films-starts-mary-magdalene-bibical-biopic|title=Mary Magdalene biopic to be made by King's Speech producer|first=Ben|last=Child|date=21 January 2016|website=the Guardian}}</ref> She is also adapting the novel ''The Awkward Age'', to be broadcast by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/downton-abbey-producer-carnival-films-adapting-the-awkward-age-for-the-bbc-1202286361/|title=\u2018Downton Abbey\u2019 Producer Carnival Films Adapting \u2018The Awkward Age\u2019 For The BBC|first=Peter|last=White|date=12 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Radio==\nEdmundson has adapted numerous literary classics for [[BBC Radio 4]], including ''[[The Voyage Out]]'' in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/radio4/fm/2006-03-20|title=BBC Radio 4 FM - 20 March 2006 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> ''[[The Mayor of Casterbridge]]'' in 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00bdmtx|title=The Mayor Of Casterbridge, Classic Serial - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC}}</ref> and ''[[Sense and Sensibility]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b038btbr|title=Sense and Sensibility, Classic Serial - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nEdmundson has been a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsliterature.org/fellows/current-fellows/|title=Royal Society of Literature  \u00bb Current RSL Fellows|website=rsliterature.org}}</ref>\n\n*1992 [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Award]] for ''Anna Karenina''\n*1992 [[TMA Award]] for ''Anna Karenina''\n*1993 [[John Whiting Award]] winner for ''The Clearing''<ref name=\"windhamcampbell.org\"/>\n*1994 [[TMA Award]] for ''The Clearing'' and ''The Mill on the Floss''<ref name=\"windhamcampbell.org\"/>\n*Nomination: 1996 Writers' Guild Award for Best Play for ''War and Peace''\n*Nomination: 2004 [[TMA Award]] for Best Touring Production for ''Gone to Earth''<ref name=\"londontheatre.co.uk\"/>\n*2005 [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Award]] for ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]''\n*Nomination: 2006 [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Play]] for ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]''<ref name=\"olivierawards.com\"/>\n*Nomination: 2009 [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical]] for ''[[Zorro (musical)|Zorro]]''<ref name=\"olivierawards.com1\"/>\n*Nomination: 2012 [[Evening Standard Theatre Awards]]' Ned Sherrin Award for Best Musical for ''Swallows and Amazons''<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\"/>\n*2015 [[Windham\u2013Campbell Literature Prize]] (Drama)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://windhamcampbell.org/2015/winner/helen-edmundson |title=Prize Citation for Helen Edmundson |publisher=Windham\u2013Campbell Literature Prize |date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Broadcasting Press Guild|Broadcasting Press Guild Award]] for Best Single Drama for ''[[An Inspector Calls (2015 TV film)|An Inspector Calls]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingpressguild.org/bpg-awards/bpg-awards-2016/|title=2016|date=12 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|1779951}}\n* Barbara Slaughter, [http://www.wsws.org/articles/2012/jun2012/edmu-j13.shtml \"An interview with Helen Edmundson, author of ''Mary Shelley''\"], [[World Socialist Web Site]], 13 June 2012.\n\n{{John Whiting Award|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edmundson, Helen}}\n[[Category: Helen Edmundson]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:British women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:British screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:British radio writers]]\n[[Category:Women radio writers]]\n[[Category:British television writers]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British playwright and screenwriter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Helen Edmundson\n| birth_date    = 1964\n| birth_place   = Liverpool, England, UK\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = Playwright, Screenwriter\n}}\n\n'''Helen Edmundson''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 1964) is a British [[playwright]] and [[screenwriter]]. She has won awards and critical acclaim both for her original writing and for her adaptations of various literary classics for the stage and screen.\n\n==Early life==\nEdmundson was born in [[Liverpool]], in 1964.<ref name=\"clearing\">{{cite book|last1=Edmundson|first1=Helen|title=The Clearing|date=2002|publisher=Nick Hern Books|location=London|isbn=1854592815}}</ref> Most of her childhood was spent on the [[Wirral Peninsula|Wirral]] and in [[Chester]].<ref name=\"clearing\"/> Edmundson studied drama at [[Manchester University]].<ref name=\"clearing\"/> After her studies, Edmundson acted with Red Stockings, a female agit-prop company, for whom she wrote the musical comedy ''Ladies in the Lift'' in 1988.<ref name=\"clearing\"/> This was her first solo attempt at writing for the stage. After leaving Red Stockings, she acted throughout northwest England.<ref name=\"clearing\"/>\n\n==Theatre==\n===1990s===\nEdmundson's first play ''Flying'' was produced at the [[National Theatre Studio]] in 1990. In 1992, her adaptation of ''[[Anna Karenina]]'', produced by [[Shared Experience]], won a [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] Award and a [[Theatre Awards UK|TMA Award]]; the production toured nationally and internationally.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nickhernbooks.co.uk/helen-edmundson|title=Nick Hern Books &#124; About Helen Edmundson|website=Nick Hern Books|accessdate=Oct 9, 2019}}</ref> In 1993, Edmundson's original play ''The Clearing'', which won the [[John Whiting Award]], was staged at the [[Bush Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre--civil-strife-paul-taylor-reviews-helen-edmundsons-the-clearing-at-the-bush-1507694.html|title=THEATRE / Civil strife: Paul Taylor reviews Helen Edmundson's The|publisher=}}</ref> In 1994, her adaptation of ''[[The Mill on the Floss]]'' was also produced by Shared Experience, again touring nationally and internationally; Edmundson won a Time Out Award for ''The Clearing'' and ''The Mill on the Floss''.<ref name=\"windhamcampbell.org\">{{cite web|url=http://windhamcampbell.org/2015/winner/helen-edmundson|title=Helen Edmundson|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> In 1996, Shared Experience staged her adaptation of ''[[War and Peace]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/war-of-the-words-1338952.html|title=War of the words|publisher=}}</ref> in a production starring [[British Academy Television Awards|BAFTA Award]]-nominee [[Anne-Marie Duff]]; the play was nominated for a Writers' Guild Award for Best Play.\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2002, Edmundson's play ''Mother Teresa is Dead'' was produced at the [[Royal Court Theatre]]. In 2004, her adaptation of ''Gone to Earth'' was produced by Shared Experience at the [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)|Lyric Hammersmith]] and on tour; it was nominated for a [[TMA Award]].<ref name=\"londontheatre.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.londontheatre.co.uk/londontheatre/news/sep04/17sep04tma.htm|title=TMA Theatre Awards 2004 nominations announced|date=8 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Edmundson's adaptation of ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]'' premiered at the National Theatre in November 2005, starring [[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]]-winner [[Bertie Carvel]] and [[Tony Award]]-nominee [[Paul Ritter (actor)|Paul Ritter]]; Edmundson received a Time Out Award and was nominated for an Olivier Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/nov/16/theatre|author=[[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]]|title=Coram Boy|date=16 November 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"olivierawards.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/winners/view/item98373/olivier-winners-2006/|title=Olivier Winners 2006|publisher=}}</ref> The play came back for a revival at the same venue a year later, again starring Carvel. Her adaptation of ''[[Orestes (play)|Orestes]]'', toured in the UK and played at the [[Tricycle Theatre]] with Shared Experience in 2006. ''Coram Boy'' was revived at the [[Imperial Theatre]] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 2007, starring [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]]-winner [[Uzo Aduba]] and Tony Award-nominee [[Jan Maxwell]], receiving six Tony Award nominations. In 2008, Edmundson amended her adaptation of ''War and Peace'', turning it into a two-part play; this production was staged by Shared Experience and Nottingham Playhouse before touring. In the same year, her musical adaptation of ''[[Zorro (musical)|Zorro]]'' was produced at the [[Garrick Theatre]], starring Olivier Award-winner [[Lesli Margherita]] and Olivier Award-nominee [[Emma Williams (actress)|Emma Williams]]; Edmundson was nominated for an Olivier Award for Best New Musical.<ref name=\"olivierawards.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/winners/view/item106339/olivier-winners-2009/|title=Olivier Awards Winners 2009 -Official London Theatre|publisher=}}</ref> In 2009, Edmundson's adaptation of ''[[Life Is a Dream]]'' was produced at the [[Donmar Warehouse]], starring BAFTA Award-winner [[Dominic West]].\n\n===2010s===\nIn 2010, Edmundson's musical adaptation of ''[[Swallows and Amazons]]'' was first produced at the [[Bristol Old Vic]], directed by Tony Award-winner [[Tom Morris (director)|Tom Morris]]. The next year, the show transferred to the [[Vaudeville Theatre]]; the play was nominated for an [[Evening Standard Theatre Award]].<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/evening-standard-theatre-awards-adrian-lester-and-his-writer-wife-lolita-chakrabarti-shortlisted-8306478.html|title=Evening Standard Theatre Awards: Adrian Lester and his writer wife|publisher=}}</ref> Edmundson took part in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s 2011 project ''[[Sixty-Six Books]]'', for which artists wrote a piece based upon a book of the [[King James Bible]]; Edmundson wrote a piece entitled ''In the night, a promise'', based on ''[[Book of Zephaniah|Zephaniah]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090950/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |archivedate=2011-07-04 }}</ref> The same year, her adaptation of ''Coram Boy'' was revived at the Bristol Old Vic. In 2012, her play about [[Juana In\u00e9s de la Cruz]], ''[[The Heresy of Love]]'', was produced by the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at the [[Swan Theatre (Stratford)|Swan Theatre]] in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].<ref>[http://www.rsc.org.uk/explore/other-writers/the-heresy-of-love.aspx ''The Heresy of Love''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140414053138/http://www.rsc.org.uk/explore/other-writers/the-heresy-of-love.aspx |date=2014-04-14 }}, RSC.</ref> The same year, Edmundson's adaptation of ''Swallows and Amazons'' was revived for a national tour. Also in 2012, Edmundson's play ''Mary Shelley'' was produced on a nationwide tour, including the Tricycle Theatre and the [[Liverpool Playhouse]], by Shared Experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sharedexperience.org.uk/maryshelley.html|title=Shared Experience - Productions - Mary Shelley|first=|last=?|website=www.sharedexperience.org.uk}}</ref> In 2013, her adaptation of ''[[Mephisto (novel)|Mephisto]]'' was produced at the [[Altonaer Theater]] in [[Hamburg]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dramaonlinelibrary.com/playwrights/helen-edmundson-iid-135921|title=Edmundson, Helen - Drama Online|website=www.dramaonlinelibrary.com|accessdate=Oct 9, 2019}}</ref> In 2014, Edmundson's adaptation of novel ''[[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Raquin]]'' was produced at the [[Theatre Royal, Bath]], starring Olivier Award-winners [[Alison Steadman]] and [[Desmond Barrit]]. In 2015, ''The Heresy of Love'' was revived for a run at [[Shakespeare's Globe]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Heresy of Love |url=http://www.shakespearesglobe.com/discovery-space/previous-productions/the-heresy-of-love |website=Shakespeare's Globe |accessdate=20 September 2018 |year=2015}}. Written by Helen Edmundson and directed by John Dove.</ref> Edmundson's adaptation of ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Raquin'' was produced by [[Roundabout Theatre Company]] at [[Studio 54]] on Broadway from 2015 to 2016, starring [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-nominee [[Keira Knightley]] and Tony Award-winner [[Judith Light]]; the play was nominated for Outstanding New Broadway Play at the 2016 [[Outer Critics Circle Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/things-to-do/therese-raquin|title=Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Raquin - Theater in New York|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-ThereseRaquin-Knightly-2015>{{cite news|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse|title=Keira Knightley, Making Her Broadway Debut, Is Not Afraid of the Dark|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/25/theater/keira-knightley-making-her-broadway-debut-is-not-afraid-of-the-dark.html|accessdate=21 October 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=21 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/2016-outer-critics-circle-nominees-announced-com-347165|title=2016 Outer Critics Circle Nominees Announced - Playbill|website=Playbill}}</ref> Simultaneously, the RSC premiered her play ''[[Queen Anne (play)|Queen Anne]]'' in Stratford.<ref>Matthew Hemley, [http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/production/2015/02/rsc-unveils-winter-2015-season-antony-sher-lear/ \"RSC unveils winter 2015 season and Antony Sher as Lear\"], ''The Stage''.</ref> In 2017, the RSC produced ''Queen Anne'' at the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]], starring [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]]-winner [[Romola Garai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-38831153|title=Romola Garai takes on aristocratic role|date=1 February 2017|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2017/feb/01/royal-shakespeare-company-to-stage-robert-harriss-cicero-trilogy|title=Royal Shakespeare Company to stage Robert Harris's Cicero trilogy|first=Maev|last=Kennedy|date=1 February 2017|website=the Guardian}}</ref> From April to August 2019, Edmundson's adaptation of ''[[Small Island (novel)|Small Island]]'' was produced at the National Theatre, directed by its artistic director, Olivier Award-nominee [[Rufus Norris]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/oct/03/andrea-levys-small-island-novel-to-be-staged-next-year|title=Andrea Levy's Small Island novel to be staged next year|first=Mark Brown Arts|last=correspondent|date=Oct 3, 2018|accessdate=Oct 9, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the play one of the top two theatre shows of 2019.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2019/dec/17/top-10-theatre-shows-of-2019</ref>\n\n===2020s===\nEdmundson's adaptation of ''Small Island'' will be revived at the National Theatre in October 2020, again directed by Norris.<ref>https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/national-2020-kristin-scott-thomas-phaedra_50970.html</ref>\n\n==Film and television==\nEdmundson has written two short films for television: ''One Day'', broadcast on [[BBC Two]] in July 1991,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/bbctwo/england/1991-07-25|title=BBC Two England - 25 July 1991 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> and ''Stella'' for [[Channel 4]]. In 2015, she wrote two episodes of [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] drama ''[[The Suspicions of Mr Whicher]]'', ''Beyond the Pale'' and ''The Ties that Bind'', starring [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]]-winners [[Paddy Considine]] and [[Tim Pigott-Smith]]. In September of the same year, Edmundson's feature-length adaptation of ''[[An Inspector Calls (2015 TV film)|An Inspector Calls]]'', starring BAFTA Award-winners [[David Thewlis]] and [[Miranda Richardson]], was broadcast on [[BBC One]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/sep/14/bbc-an-inspector-calls-this-is-england-90|title=BBC's An Inspector Calls arrests nearly 6 million viewers|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=14 September 2015|website=the Guardian}}</ref> the adaptation won the 2016 [[Broadcasting Press Guild]] Award for Best Single Drama<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingpressguild.org/bpgawards/bpg-awards-2016/|title=2016|date=12 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and was nominated for two 2016 [[British Academy Television Craft Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awards.bafta.org/award/2016/tvcraft|title=Television Craft in 2016 - BAFTA Awards|website=awards.bafta.org}}</ref> In 2018, Edmundson wrote the film ''[[Mary Magdalene (2018 film)|Mary Magdalene]]'', which was directed by Emmy Award-nominee [[Garth Davis]] and starred Academy Award-nominees [[Rooney Mara]] and [[Joaquin Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/21/kings-speech-producer-see-saw-films-starts-mary-magdalene-bibical-biopic|title=Mary Magdalene biopic to be made by King's Speech producer|first=Ben|last=Child|date=21 January 2016|website=the Guardian}}</ref> She is also adapting the novel ''The Awkward Age'', to be broadcast by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/downton-abbey-producer-carnival-films-adapting-the-awkward-age-for-the-bbc-1202286361/|title=\u2018Downton Abbey\u2019 Producer Carnival Films Adapting \u2018The Awkward Age\u2019 For The BBC|first=Peter|last=White|date=12 February 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Radio==\nEdmundson has adapted numerous literary classics for [[BBC Radio 4]], including ''[[The Voyage Out]]'' in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/radio4/fm/2006-03-20|title=BBC Radio 4 FM - 20 March 2006 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> ''[[The Mayor of Casterbridge]]'' in 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00bdmtx|title=The Mayor Of Casterbridge, Classic Serial - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC}}</ref> and ''[[Sense and Sensibility]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b038btbr|title=Sense and Sensibility, Classic Serial - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nEdmundson has been a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsliterature.org/fellows/current-fellows/|title=Royal Society of Literature  \u00bb Current RSL Fellows|website=rsliterature.org}}</ref>\n\n*1992 [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Award]] for ''Anna Karenina''\n*1992 [[TMA Award]] for ''Anna Karenina''\n*1993 [[John Whiting Award]] winner for ''The Clearing''<ref name=\"windhamcampbell.org\"/>\n*1994 [[TMA Award]] for ''The Clearing'' and ''The Mill on the Floss''<ref name=\"windhamcampbell.org\"/>\n*Nomination: 1996 Writers' Guild Award for Best Play for ''War and Peace''\n*Nomination: 2004 [[TMA Award]] for Best Touring Production for ''Gone to Earth''<ref name=\"londontheatre.co.uk\"/>\n*2005 [[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out Award]] for ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]''\n*Nomination: 2006 [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Play]] for ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]''<ref name=\"olivierawards.com\"/>\n*Nomination: 2009 [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical]] for ''[[Zorro (musical)|Zorro]]''<ref name=\"olivierawards.com1\"/>\n*Nomination: 2012 [[Evening Standard Theatre Awards]]' Ned Sherrin Award for Best Musical for ''Swallows and Amazons''<ref name=\"standard.co.uk\"/>\n*2015 [[Windham\u2013Campbell Literature Prize]] (Drama)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://windhamcampbell.org/2015/winner/helen-edmundson |title=Prize Citation for Helen Edmundson |publisher=Windham\u2013Campbell Literature Prize |date=February 24, 2015 |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\n*2016 [[Broadcasting Press Guild|Broadcasting Press Guild Award]] for Best Single Drama for ''[[An Inspector Calls (2015 TV film)|An Inspector Calls]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingpressguild.org/bpg-awards/bpg-awards-2016/|title=2016|date=12 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|1779951}}\n* Barbara Slaughter, [http://www.wsws.org/articles/2012/jun2012/edmu-j13.shtml \"An interview with Helen Edmundson, author of ''Mary Shelley''\"], [[World Socialist Web Site]], 13 June 2012.\n\n{{John Whiting Award|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edmundson, Helen}}\n[[Category: Helen Edmundson]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Writers from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:British women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:British screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:British radio writers]]\n[[Category:Women radio writers]]\n[[Category:British television writers]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n", "name_user": "The Raincloud Kid", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2010s:Corrected grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helen_Edmundson"}
{"title_page": "Marquette, Michigan", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name = Marquette, Michigan\n| settlement_type = City\n| image_skyline = Downtown Marquette, Michigan in Autumn (43657514144).jpg\n| imagesize = 275\n| image_caption = Downtown Marquette along [[U.S. Route 41 Business (Marquette, Michigan)|Front Street]]\n| image_map = Marquette, MI location.png\n| mapsize = 250\n| map_caption = Location within [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]]\n| pushpin_map = Michigan\n| pushpin_label_position = left<!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n| pushpin_label = Marquette\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within the state of Michigan\n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_type1 = State\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n| subdivision_name = United States\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Michigan]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette]]\n| government_type = [[Council\u2013manager government|Commission-Manager]]\n| leader_title = Mayor\n| leader_name = Jenna Smith<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.uppermichiganssource.com/content/news/New-Mayor-of-Marquette-is-Jenna-Smith-564834871.html |title = New Mayor of Marquette is Jenna Smith |last = Mason-Little |first = Taylor |date = November 12, 2019 |work = Upper Michigan's Source |location = Negaunee, Michigan |publisher = [[WLUC-TV]] |language = en |access-date = December 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| leader_title1 = [[City manager]]\n| leader_name1 = L. Michael Angeli<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.miningjournal.net/page/content.detail/id/626012/Angeli-given-manager-s-position.html |title = Angeli given manager's position |work = [[The Mining Journal]] |location = Marquette, Michigan |last = Jarvi |first = Ryan |date = September 15, 2015 |access-date = September 22, 2015 }}</ref>\n| established_date = \n<!-- Area -->\n| unit_pref = Imperial\n| area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_26.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| area_magnitude = \n| area_total_km2 = 50.24\n| area_land_km2 = 29.36\n| area_water_km2 = 20.87\n| area_total_sq_mi = 19.40\n| area_land_sq_mi = 11.34\n| area_water_sq_mi = 8.06\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n| population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_est = 20680\n| pop_est_as_of = 2018\n| population_note = \n| population_total = 21355\n| population_metro = 67,077\n| population_density_km2 = 702.56\n| population_density_sq_mi = 1819.62\n| timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset = -5\n| timezone_DST = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST = -4\n| coordinates = {{coord|46|32|47|N|87|24|24|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_m = 203\n| elevation_ft = 633<ref>{{cite web |url = http://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=46.5475825&lon=-87.39559539999999&site=all&smap=1&searchresult=Marquette%2C%20MI%2C%20USA#.UwZgA8Gzm8o |title = NOAA National Weather Service }}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|http://www.marquettemi.gov|Official website}}\n| postal_code_type = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code = 49855\n| area_code = [[Area code 906|906]]\n| blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info = 26-51900<ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web |url = https://www.census.gov |publisher = United States Census Bureau |access-date = January 31, 2008 |title = U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n| blank1_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info = 0631600<ref>{{Cite GNIS|0631600|Marquette}}</ref>\n| footnotes = \n| pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n| name = \n}}\n\n'''Marquette''' is a city in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]] and the [[county seat]] of [[Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web |url = http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |access-date = June 7, 2011 |title = Find a County |publisher = National Association of Counties }}</ref> The population was 21,355 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], making it the largest city of the state's [[Upper Peninsula]]. Marquette is a major port on [[Lake Superior]], known primarily for elitists and hipsters [[iron ore]], and is the home of [[Northern Michigan University]]. In 2012, Marquette was listed among the 10 best places to retire in the United States by [[CBS MoneyWatch]].<ref>{{cite news |last = Smith |first = Nancy F. |url = https://finance.yahoo.com/news/the-10-best-places-to-retire.html |title = The 10 Best Places to Retire |work = Yahoo! Finance |date = March 8, 2012 |access-date = February 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:PereMarquetteMarquetteMI.jpg|thumb|left|Statue of [[Jacques Marquette]] in Marquette]]\n\nThe land around Marquette was known to French missionaries of the early 17th century and the trappers of the early 19th century. Development of the area did not begin until 1844, when [[William Austin Burt|William Burt]] and [[Jacob Houghton]] (the brother of geologist [[Douglass Houghton]]) discovered iron deposits near Teal Lake west of Marquette. In 1845, Jackson Mining Company, the first organized mining company in the region, was formed.<ref name=eckert>{{cite book |last = Eckert |first = Kathryn Bishop |year = 2000 |title = The Sandstone Architecture of the Lake Superior Region |pages = 89\u201391 |location = Detroit |publisher = Wayne State University Press |isbn = 0-8143-2807-5 }}</ref>\n\nThe village of Marquette began on September 14, 1849, with the formation of a second iron concern, the Marquette Iron Company. Three men participated in organizing the firm: Robert J. Graveraet, who had prospected the region for ore; Edward Clark, agent for Waterman A. Fisher of [[Worcester, Massachusetts]], who financed the company, and Amos Rogers Harlow. The village was at first called New Worcester, with Harlow as the first postmaster. On August 21, 1850, the name was changed to honor [[Jacques Marquette]], the French Jesuit missionary who had explored the region. A second post office, named Carp River, was opened on October 13, 1851 by [[Peter White (Michigan)|Peter White]], who had gone there with Graveraet at age 18.<ref>{{cite journal |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ylLF0TN50sUC |title = [not listed] |journal = Inland Seas |year = 1968 |via = [[Google Books]] }}{{full citation needed|date= March 2015}}</ref> Harlow closed his post office in August 1852. The Marquette Iron Company failed, while its successor, the [[Cleveland Iron Mining Company]], flourished and had the village [[plat]]ted in 1854. The plat was recorded by Peter White. White's office was renamed as Marquette in April 1856, and the village was incorporated in 1859. It was incorporated as a city in 1871.<ref name=\"Romig\">{{cite book |last = Romig |first = Walter |year = 1986 |title = Michigan Place Names |origyear = 1973 |publisher = Wayne State University Press |location = Detroit |isbn = 0-8143-1838-X }}</ref>\n\n[[File:2009-0618-UP002-MarquetteStPeters.jpg|thumb|[[St. Peter Cathedral, Marquette|St. Peter Cathedral]]]]\nDuring the 1850s, Marquette was linked by rail to numerous mines and became the leading shipping center of the Upper Peninsula. The first [[ore dock|ore pocket dock]], designed by an early town leader, John Burt, was built by the Cleveland Iron Mining Company in 1859.<ref name=bogue>{{cite book |last = Bogue |first = Margaret Beattie |year = 2007 |title = Around the Shores of Lake Superior: A Guide to Historic Sites |pages = 237\u201339 |location = Madison |publisher = [[University of Wisconsin Press]] |isbn = 978-0-299-22174-4 }}</ref> By 1862, the city had a population of over 1,600 and a soaring economy.<ref name=eckert/>\n\nIn the late 19th century, during the height of iron mining, Marquette became nationally known as a summer haven. Visitors brought in by Great Lakes passenger [[steamships]] filled the city's hotels and resorts.<ref name=bogue/>\n\nSouth of the city, [[K. I. Sawyer Air Force Base]] was an important [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] installation during the [[Cold War]], host to [[B-52H]] bombers and [[KC-135]] tankers of the [[Strategic Air Command]], as well as a fighter interceptor squadron. The base closed in September 1995, and is now the county's [[Sawyer International Airport]].\n\nMarquette continues to be a shipping port for [[hematite]] ores and, today, enriched iron ore pellets, from nearby mines and pelletizing plants. About 7.9 million gross tons of pelletized iron ore passed through Marquette's Presque Isle Harbor in 2005.<ref name=bogue/>\n\nThe Roman Catholic Bishop [[Frederic Baraga]] is buried at [[St. Peter Cathedral, Marquette|St. Peter Cathedral]], which is the center for the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Marquette|Diocese of Marquette]].\n\n===Postal and philatelic history===\nIn addition to the Marquette #1 Post Office there is the \"Northern Michigan University Bookstore Contract Station #384\".<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.postmarks.org/pop/2100/2187.htm |title = Post Office Photo Collection |publisher = Post Mark Collectors Club }}</ref>\n\nThe [[first day of issue]] of a [[postal card]] showing Bishop Frederic Baraga took place in Marquette on June 29, 1984,<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Murphy |first1 = Joe |date = June 30, 1984 |title = Postal Card Honors Work of Snowshoe Priest |work = [[The Mining Journal]] |location = Marquette, MI |page = 1A |issn = 0898-4964 }}</ref> and that of the Wonders of America Lake Superior stamp<ref>{{cite web |url = http://arago.si.edu/index.asp?con=2&cmd=1&fid=&fid=2046545&id=192585&img=1&mode=2&pg=1&tid=204653 |title = 39c Lake Superior single |publisher = Arago.com |access-date = April 23, 2013 }}</ref> on May 27, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://mqtmaritimemuseum.com/06-stamp.html |publisher = Marquette Maritime Museum |title = Dedication of Wonders of America Lake Superior Stamp |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120520074937/http://mqtmaritimemuseum.com/06-stamp.html |archive-date = May 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography and climate==\n\n===Geography===\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|19.45|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|11.39|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|8.06|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title = US Gazetteer files 2010 |url = https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]] |access-date = November 25, 2012 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archive-date = July 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe city includes several small islands (principally Middle Island, Gull Island, Lover's Island, Presque Isle Pt. Rocks, White Rocks, Ripley Rock, and Picnic Rocks) in Lake Superior. The [[Marquette Underwater Preserve]] lies immediately offshore.\n\n[[Marquette Mountain]], used for skiing, is located in the city, as is most of the land of [[Marquette Branch Prison]] of the [[Michigan Department of Corrections]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.michigan.gov/corrections/1,1607,7-119-1381_1388-5326--,00.html |publisher = Michigan Department of Corrections |title = Marquette Branch Prison }}</ref> The town of [[Trowbridge Park, Michigan|Trowbridge Park]] (under [[Marquette Township, Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette Township]]), is located to the west, [[Sands Township, Marquette County, Michigan|Sands Township]] to the south, and [[Marquette Township, Marquette County, Michigan|Marquette Township]] to the northwest of the city.\n\n===Climate===\nThe climate is a [[humid continental climate|hemiboreal humid continental]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen:]] ''Dfb'') with four distinct seasons that is strongly moderated by [[Lake Superior]] and is located in [[Hardiness zone|Plant Hardiness zone]] 5b.<ref name = USDA>{{cite map |url = http://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/PHZMWeb/ |title = USDA Plant Hardiness Zone Map |publisher = United States Department of Agriculture |access-date = May 10, 2013 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140227032333/http://planthardiness.ars.usda.gov/PHZMWeb/ |archivedate = February 27, 2014 |url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=34727&cityname=Marquette,+Michigan,+United+States+of+America|title=Marquette, Michigan K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref> Winters are long and cold with a January average of {{convert|18.8|\u00b0F|1}}. Winter temperatures are slightly warmer than inland locations at a similar latitude due to the release of the heat stored by the lake, which moderates the climate.<ref name = EPA>{{cite web |url = http://www.epa.gov/glnpo/atlas/glat-ch2.html#Climate |title = Natural Processes in the Great Lakes |work = The Great Lakes An Environmental Atlas and Resource Book |publisher = Environmental Protection Agency |access-date = May 10, 2013 }}</ref> On average, there are 11.6&nbsp;days annually where the minimum temperature reaches {{convert|0|\u00b0F}} and 73&nbsp;days with a maximum at or below freezing, including a majority of days during meteorological winter (December thru February).<ref name=NCDC-M /> \n\nBeing located in the [[snowbelt|snowbelt region]], Marquette receives a significant amount of snowfall during the winter months, mostly from [[lake-effect snow]]. Because [[Lake Superior]] rarely freezes over completely, this enables lake effect snow to persist throughout winter, making Marquette the third snowiest location in the contiguous United States as reported by the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] with an average annual snowfall of {{convert|149.1|in|m|2|disp=or}}.<ref name=\"NOAA-M\" /> The snow depth in winter usually exceeds {{convert|10|in|m|2|disp=or}}.<ref name=\"NCDC-M\" /> Marquette is the city with the deepest snow depths with a population of more than 20,000 in the [[United States|US]] (and one of the largest in [[North America]] outside the western Cordillera or [[eastern Canada]]), as temperatures remain low throughout the winter and cold, dry air is intercepted by the [[Great Lakes]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.windy.com/|title=Windy as forecasted|last=SE|first=Windyty|website=www.windy.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\nThe warmest months, July and August, each average {{convert|66.6|\u00b0F|1}}, showing somewhat of a [[seasonal lag]]. The surrounding lake cools summertime temperatures<ref name = EPA /> and as a result, temperatures above {{convert|90|\u00b0F|1}} are rare, with only 3.4 days per year.<ref name=NCDC-M /> Spring and fall are transitional seasons that are generally mild though highly variable due to the alternation of air masses moving quickly. Spring is usually cooler than fall because the surrounding lake is slower to warm than the land, while in fall the lake releases heat, warming the area.<ref name = EPA />\n\nMarquette receives {{convert|29|in|0|abbr=on}} of precipitation per year, which is fairly evenly distributed throughout the year, though September and October are the wettest months with January and February being the driest. The average window for morning freezes is October 15 thru May 7.<ref name=NCDC-M /> The highest temperature ever recorded in Marquette was {{convert|108|\u00b0F|0}} on July 15, 1901 and the lowest was {{convert|\u221233|\u00b0F|0}} on February 8, 1861.<ref name=NCDC-M /> Marquette receives an average of 2,294 hours of sunshine per year or 51 percent of possible sunshine, ranging from a low of 29 percent in December to a high of 68 percent in July.<ref name = NCDC1 />\n\nThe City of Marquette has received national attention for its measures to [[Climate change adaptation|adapt to climate change]], such as coastline restoration and moving portions of Lakeshore Boulevard which are flooded by [[Lake Superior]] 100 yards inland. Property owners are required to maintain \u201c[[riparian buffer]]s\u201d of native plants along waterways. A county task force has created a guidebook in cooperation with the University of Michigan for landscaping which can reduce the habitat for disease-bearing ticks.\u00a0A federally funded [[Storm drain|stormwater drain]] project will route [[Surface runoff|runoff]] which flows into Lake Superior into [[Wetland|restored wetlands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgemi.com/michigan-environment-watch/marquette-girds-climate-change-michigans-upper-peninsula|title=Marquette girds for climate change in Michigan's Upper Peninsula|last=Malewitz|first=Jim|date=2019-11-11|website=Bridge, Michigan Environment Watch|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>  \n<section begin=\"weather box\" />{{Weather box\n|collapsed=<includeonly>Y</includeonly>\n|location = Marquette (1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1857\u2013present)\n|single line = y\n|Jan record high F =  57\n|Feb record high F =  69\n|Mar record high F =  82\n|Apr record high F =  91\n|May record high F = 100\n|Jun record high F = 101\n|Jul record high F = 108\n|Aug record high F = 102\n|Sep record high F =  98\n|Oct record high F =  89\n|Nov record high F =  74\n|Dec record high F =  60\n\n|Jan avg record high F = 42.6\n|Feb avg record high F = 47.1\n|Mar avg record high F = 58.5\n|Apr avg record high F = 74.2\n|May avg record high F = 83.5\n|Jun avg record high F = 87.8\n|Jul avg record high F = 90.7\n|Aug avg record high F = 90.1\n|Sep avg record high F = 85.3\n|Oct avg record h